The term of decadence with similar meanings include 'degeneration' and 'corruption'. 'Decadent' was the term of the mid-1880s and 'overly influential' in Europe. There are two broad ways of analysing decadence. The first is historical; 'modern' and 'madhouse' production. The vital idea from Epicurus includes ‘foolishness’ into the human which is called a ‘piece of fate’. Decadent’ are defined as a defective or decadent form of life. The courage that is impossible in the herd. The meaning of decadence is not often found. Decadent’ are defined as a form of life that has (i) overcome nihilism, (ii) also overcome the temptation of pity for higher types that are incapable of further development, (iii) overcome nausea likewise at the thought of the development of human values, and (iv) overcome nausea both at the thought of the development of human values, but also at the fact that there is no object of knowledge about the effects of atoms or the development of concepts of soul, or of power or of becoming. Such periods of history are characterized by a transformation of the nature of life from the systematic assumption to human beings of certain values from which they were raised, and which then lost sight of their limits. Such decadence in substance is called a degeneration. Where

